# 🔓 OPTION 1: Self-host GPU + Public API (quick, but risky)
# 🧠 Goal

# Your GPU (home/on-prem) runs the model → internet users (your phone) can call it.

# 🧱 Architecture
# 📱 Phone → 🌍 Internet → 🌐 Public URL → 🖥️ Your GPU Server (LLM API)
# 🛠️ Step-by-step
# 1) Run your model as an API

# Use Ollama (simplest):

# ollama serve   # starts server at http://localhost:11434
# ollama run llama3

# Test locally:

# curl http://localhost:11434/api/chat -d '{
#   "model":"llama3",
#   "messages":[{"role":"user","content":"hello"}]
# }'
# 2) Expose it to the internet (2 ways)
# 🔹 Way A (fast): Tunnel with ngrok
# ngrok http 11434

# You’ll get:

# https://abc123.ngrok-free.app

# 👉 Now your phone can call:

# fetch("https://abc123.ngrok-free.app/api/chat", {...})

# Pros: 2 minutes setup
# Cons: temporary URL, not secure for real data





# 🔹 Way B (real): Public IP + reverse proxy with NGINX
# a) Get a public IP
# Home router port-forward OR
# VPS (better)
# b) Install NGINX
# sudo apt install nginx
# c) Configure proxy
# server {
#     listen 80;

#     location /ai/ {
#         proxy_pass http://localhost:11434/;
#     }
# }
# d) (Important) Add HTTPS

# Use Let’s Encrypt (certbot):

# sudo apt install certbot python3-certbot-nginx
# sudo certbot --nginx
# e) Call from React
# fetch("https://yourdomain.com/ai/api/chat", {...})
# ⚠️ Why “risky”?
# Public exposure → attacks, scraping
# No network isolation
# Must add auth, rate limits, WAF